As someone who's had one of these from the early 80s, I'll say these things were everywhere, much of them clones. The original walkmans were large and clunky, but they advanced to where these things were not much bigger than the cassettes themselves. Another thing to mention is that tapes were better media to replicate music than most people think. Well recorded cassettes sounded fantastic, that's why they still master to tape even to this day. Still, they do wear from use and suffer jitters when moving quickly, similar to how early iPods' hard disk skipped.

Finally, my original walkman works well even after 40 years, and I didn't have to fix anything, though I could I guess if/when it breaks. That's one hell of a quality manufacturing, when I think about how many iPods and cell phones I had to throw away.

I do have to say, and trust me I love this video its very good stuff, but the Walkman was not the first personal music player. For anyone who is interested:

--I would say that the 1924 Mikiphone Record Player was the first truly "portable" personal music player. (As long as you don't define personal as using headphones ;) It was a simple wind up gramophone that played shellac 78rpm records acoustically so it required no electricity. Techmoan has a good video on a reproduction model of these.

--Although you couldn't choose the exact music you wanted to listen to, you can't possibly forget the transistor radio. The 1954 Regency TR-1 was the first portable transistor radio.

--If you don't think that those devices fit the bill, Sony had made the predecessor to the Walkman (The Sony TC-50) nearly 10 years before the Walkman's release in 1979. In fact the TC-50 was taken on the Apollo 11 mission to the moon where it functioned valiantly. (Techmoan also has a good video on this device)

I wasn't going to comment but when I heart that guy at 22:34 say sound was more HiFi I completely lost it. Shop throwing the word HiFi around as if it makes it cool or something. HiFi is high fidelity something I can tell you no CD will give you. Digital music sounds punchier. Controlled. More forward almost.

I prefer vinyl and tape. Those were analogue. The amount of detail you could hear on these two types was out of this world compared to compressed quality of the CD even to this day.

I do listen to Tidal, Spotify but I also have a vinyl and cassette deck. The sound is more laid back and not as ONE NOTE as I would perfectly describe it on CD. The songs sound more dynamic. By dynamic I mean the fluctuations within the lows (quieter parts) and highs (louder parts) of the song. The depth of that sound is amazing. The bass isn't just one flat note. You can actually hear the reverb on a drum. You can hear white noise o a recording. That obviously depends on the recording and mastering engineer as well as how well the vinyl was pressed and how good of a quality the cassette is. Yes, it is harder to deal with physical formats and it isn't for everybody but that is what true HiFi is. Those were the formats that started the whole HiFi world and the equipment to take advantage of it which were separate components. Im just very passionate about this subject and I always get angry when I hear people using words just to associate or qualify something better or worse than it is.
The Vinyl player is a Rega Planar 2 and the amplifier is an Audiolab 6000A. The cassette player is a Kenwood KX-503 (40years old).
Now the diskman would blow your mind. I remember buying a diskman with higher skip playability. It would buffer the song ahead so if it skipped, it would still continue playing the song

Fyi, Sony is still making Walkmans. The Walkman brand is now used by Sony as their line of DAPs ( Digital Audio Player ) which are a step above the usual MP3 player as it supports high end codecs like FLAC, and it usually has a variety of DACs and amplifiers built in to push sound quality into even higher levels. They also implement many different software derived sound enhancing features like DSEE-HX and AptX HD.

However, unlike the original Walkman, the current Walkman is not mainstream. It is aimed at audio enthusiasts and audiophiles that don't want to lose audio quality while bringing their music with them. Meanwhile the mainstream is listening to music on smartphones via spotify, Apple music, and so on. However, despite that, the Walkman still does exist, and in my opinion, still as cool as ever.

I'm a young person in terms of the people who ACTUALLY grew up with sony walkmans as I was born in 2001. For me, I just used them because of guardians of the galaxy, and wanted a cassette player, this was roughly back in 2016. I didn't own a phone, nor a mp3 player, and cassette tapes were easier for me to come by, so I asked my aunt's boyfriend for a sony walkman, and he gave me one.

Then I got a Sports 2 white walkman at a yardsale for free, and it had those awesome headphones that were like earbuds that went inside your ears, which i wish they'd still make to this day, as that was such an ingenious design and the audio was pretty good!

then that walkman broke, along with the cool ass headphones (repairing walkmans wasn't something that we could afford, and we were too lazy to do it anyways), and I went back to my previous walkman, until THAT broke in the summer of 2017. Luckily, my uncle in california, where we were staying at the time for vacation, revealed to me he had an original yellow Sony Sports WM-AF59, that still worked, and had an even COOLER looking pair of headphones, which sadly also broke, BUT the walkman still works to this day, and it is my current sony walkman. Despite not having megabass like my other walkmans, it's by far the coolest looking walkman. I feel like i'm a 90's kid whenever i use it, and both the radio and tape deck still work! (although, i had to play around with the speed of the deck, as sometimes the tapes would play faster than normal.) I don't use the walkman as much anymore, as i eventually got an iphone, then an ipod when the iphone broke, but i still use it whenever I go on car trips, or somewhere without wifi, as I don't have much songs in itunes.

I also used to use it at school, because I loved the reactions the teachers and students gave me whenever i did bring it, the teachers were filled with nostalgia, and the students would react as if i brought something from an alien world. Aww I miss my old walkman. I was born 4 years after the first one was released but I used it up until mp3-players started to arrive. I've always wanted to bring my music with me, so I tried out the different portable music players through the years and up until mp3-players (I refuse to say iPods, since I never got one of those and there were so many different players besides iPods), walkman was the only one that played my music without skipping every few seconds.

Both the portable cd-player and minidisc player had that problem and I hated it. On the cd-player it was so bad that I actually threw it on asphalt with all the power the 13 yo me had back then, because I was so mad! All I wanted was to listen to my music! I had bought it for my own money, my parents made me get a one day/week job from the day I turned 13 to make me realise the value of money. So I knew what it was worth, and yet I still threw it on the ground, that's how mad I was. Then I went home and got my walkman instead and it even had a fm-radio.

I had it for 20 years, it still worked, but I gave it away, I thought I would never listen to cassette tapes again, since the phones was good enough now. And now I regret that, because I've found tapes that don't exist on cd and it's not the same thing to listen on it on Youtube. I want to listen to Svingelskogen damn it! :P

Generation X here: No one would ever fly and land on the ground with their athletic Walkman like you did. It was still a frickin' expensive piece of technology. You could run/jog with it, exercise (aerobics was HUGE in the 80's & 90's), roller-skate, ice-skate. You weren't trying to play team games with it on. One thing I wish those professors had mentioned was how the Sony Walkman lightweight headphones themselves had magic in them. Before those headphones and the Walkman, everyone had listened to music through regular large headphones on their stereo, transistor radios, record players (which had those small white single output earphones, beginning in the early 60's), etc., but the Walkman headphones weren't just lightweight, the sound was incomparable, especially when they first came out in 79 and 80. After that, when you bought them, you could tell which ones were manufactured in the U.S. and the ones made in Japan. The Japanese headphones, even though they looked the same, were heavenly!! It was like hearing every note with every nerve in your body.

This episode is dope, but it got one thing wrong though: The portable CD-Player wasn't the end of the Walkman by any means. Both technologies coexisted right until the first affordable MP3 players came into play. The reason was the ever so slightly smaller form factor, and the fact that most people didn't have a CD recorder or burner until the early 2000s, meaning that it was still much more convenient (and affordable!) to put together a mixtape rather than a mix CD. By the time CD burners became household items, the MP3 player was already on the rise. This lead to strange hybrid formats like the "MP3 CD" or the "ATRAC CD", which kind of defeated the whole purpose because they still came with all the disadvantages of carrying a portable CD player in the first place.

The age of the Walkman was an amazing time.  It is strange to have been apart of an era and it is so clear in you head, yet some people did not exist to experience it.  It was great recording what you wanted off the radio or copying your friend's tape and just listening to it all week.  Music felt more fluid then.  You could even plug a mic (or your headphones) into the mic jack of your boom box and record yourself and play it later in your walkman.  It was also the era of people really listening to the same songs for months instead of weeks, music stores, and really socializing about music with your friends when a new artist dropped a new album or song.  Also loved it when they invented the auto reverse button when you could flip the tape without taking it out, awesomeness!

When it comes to the Walkman and fitness, when the Walkman first hit so did the fitness boom of the 80s. Millions of people started using one to run or train in the gym. People could now listen to what they wanted instead of whatever crap was blaring over the gym speakers. From 1987-97 the number of people who said they started to walk or run for exercise went up 30%. This was due to the Walkman.

Fun Facts: The first Walkman was called the "Pressman" and it was actually first launched under another name - the 'Sound-About'. In the U.K., it was first given the name the "Stowaway.' The problem was you couldn't have multiple names and trademarks for one product to successfully sell and advertise it. Sony was having such trouble - and spending a lot of money - trying to come up with an uncopyrighted name. They would eventually go back to the 'Pressman" but swapped the 'press' for 'walk' to be able to describe what you could do while using one.

I'm of that generation.  What you don't realize is the difference it made in being able to bring YOUR music with you...that you could choose what you wanted to listen to. You weren't stuck listening to whatever someone else chose or whatever came on the radio.  And as you mentioned, it was also TRULY portable.   Yes, you could take a boombox with you but those were enormous (at least the good ones) and could weigh 20+ pounds.  Not to mention they ate batteries (D cells-expensive and heavy) like Pacman ate dots.  The walkman could fit easily in a pocket.  I remember a friend whose father brought one back from an overseas trip to Japan (they always got the newest and best versions there first and they were much cheaper than here)  It was, at that time, top of the line and was only SLIGHTLY larger than the case the tape came in.  It wasn"t about being anti social: it was about being able to be YOU.  The legacy...show me one person who does not have access to the music they like anywhere, anytime.  Whether streaming services, on their phone or an Ipod.
